<font color="#FF0000">A PROTESTER'S PERSPECTIVE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17  3:08:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Amy,<br>
  Wow!  You've chosen a wonderful subject to test your powers of discernment.  Of course there is no &quot;right answer&quot; to your question, only one that is right for each of us after we've gathered and weighed as much information as possible.<br><br>
The Vietnam War was a very hot issue when I was your age.  After studying it in depth, I became opposed to the war and participated in protest marches and rallies.  <br><br>
I am troubled that there are those who would label the Wall as a &quot;Wall of Shame.&quot;  This nation and our young became very divided on this issue...many lost sight of their objectives and the war then became the war between the pro-Vietnam and anti-Vietnam crowds.  Some of the protesters became antagonistic toward the soldiers - pretty crazy when you think that they were the ones they were trying to &quot;save.&quot;  Critical thinking skills were seriously missing for some.  As with all political movements, there will always be those who get entangled in the dogma of their &quot;side&quot; and lose all objectivity.  I would guess that those who are &quot;embarrassed&quot; by the wall fit into that category.<br><br>
The young men who fought and died in Vietnam were as brave as any that have ever fought and died for this country.  Perhaps braver - it has to be harder to face the horrors of war knowing that it will be acknowledged by few.  Those men who volunteered were often men of very high ideals (though different from mine at the time) and had the guts to stand by them.  Those who were drafted had to fight to a very &quot;uncool&quot; war which was looked down on by many of their peers.  <br><br>
As a former protester, I am so very proud of all of the young men who made sacrifices for their country...my contempt for our leaders' decision to fight as we did in Vietnam has nothing to do with my love and respect for the honorable young men, both living and dead, who gave their hearts and lives for their country.  The popularity of a war does nothing to increase or decrease the value of a hero's deeds.<br><br>
The Wall is a beautiful monument - the only &quot;shame&quot; and &quot;embarassment&quot; is in the length of time it took to properly recognize their sacrafices.  It is a monument not in support of war, but in honor of those who died in battle.  I cannot see it as something that glorifies war, but rather as a somber memorial which magnifies the tragedy of war and the gravity of not choosing peace.  I am praying that your generation will be even better caretakers of that peace that so many of my generation (both warrior and protester) hoped for.<br><br>
ANNE 
